Correlation of attributes

death<-death[complete.cases(death), ]
death <- death %>%
  mutate(maritalStatus = case_when(
    MaritalStatus == 'D'~ 0,
    MaritalStatus == 'M'~ 1,
    MaritalStatus == 'S'~ 2,
    MaritalStatus == 'U'~ 3,
    MaritalStatus == 'W'~ 4,
  ))
death$MannerOfDeath = death$MannerOfDeath-2
death_corr_atts<<-death[c('maritalStatus','ActivityCode','Age','AgeRecode12',
               'CauseRecode39',
               'MannerOfDeath','PlaceOfInjury',
               'RaceRecode3')]

deathTable<-function(){
  return(death_corr_atts)
}
corrplot(cor(death_corr_atts),method = "color",is.corr = F,addrect = 2)

death_corr_atts%>%
  gather(-AgeRecode12, -MannerOfDeath, -RaceRecode3, key = "var", value = "Value") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = Value, y = AgeRecode12, color = MannerOfDeath, shape = factor(RaceRecode3))) +
  geom_point() +
  facet_wrap(~ var, scales = "free") +
  theme_bw()

death_manipulated <- 
  death%>%
  mutate(race = case_when(RaceRecode5==1~'White',
                          RaceRecode5==2~'Black',
                          RaceRecode5==3~'American Indian',
                          RaceRecode5==4~'Asian or Pacific Islander',
                          TRUE~'other'),
         mannerofDeath = case_when(MannerOfDeath==0~'Suicide',MannerOfDeath==1~'Homicide'),
         education = case_when(
           ((EducationReportingFlag==1 & Education2003Revision==1)
              |(EducationReportingFlag==0 & Education1989Revision<9))~'elementry',
           ((EducationReportingFlag==0 & Education1989Revision<13)
              |(EducationReportingFlag==1 & Education2003Revision<4))~'high school',
          ((EducationReportingFlag==0 & Education1989Revision<18) 
              |(EducationReportingFlag==1 & Education2003Revision<9))~'college',TRUE~'Nothing'),
         mod = case_when(MethodOfDisposition=='B'~'Burial',
                                 MethodOfDisposition=='C'~'Cremation',
                                 MethodOfDisposition=='O'~'Other',TRUE~'UNKNOWN'),
         sex = case_when(
                Sex == 'M'~'Male',
                Sex == 'F'~'Female'))
# Sex
ggplot(death_manipulated)+
  geom_bar(aes(x = sex,fill = mannerofDeath),
           alpha = 0.5,position = "fill")

# Train a Generalized Linear Model

split data into train and test by rate 0.8/0.2. family is set to binomial for logistic regression.

the first time i trained the model it faced the problem of overfitting because the mannerOfDeath was deducable from CauseRecode columns so i deleted the CauseRecodes.

Compare Predicted Values with real Values

in this section we try to plot data in order to compare predicted vs actual manner of death based on different features. Data is manipulated in a way that falsely predited values is determined in 2 categories of “Falsely predicted as Homicide” and “Falsely predicted as Suicide”.

by comparing the plots we can realize that the model is trying to copy statistics!

death.comparison=h2o.cbind(death.test,death.fit)
comparison=as.data.frame(death.comparison)
comp<-comparison%>%
  filter(Age<900)%>%
  mutate(validate=case_when(
    predict==1 & MannerOfDeath==1 ~ "Homicide",
    predict==0 & MannerOfDeath==0 ~ "Suicide",
    predict==1 & MannerOfDeath==0 ~ "Falsely predicted as Homicide",
    predict==0 & MannerOfDeath==1 ~ "Falsley predicted as Suicide",
  ))

race_coded<-comp%>%
  mutate(race_encoded=case_when(
    Race==1 ~ "White",
    Race==2 ~ "Black",
    Race==3 ~ "American Indian",
    Race==4 ~ "Chinese",
    Race==5 ~ "Japanese",
    Race==18 ~ "Asian Indian",
    Race==28 ~ "Korean",
    Race==48 ~ "Vietnamese",
    Race==58 ~ "Guamanian",
    Race==68 || Race==78 ~ "Other Asian or Pacific Islander",
    TRUE ~ "unknown"
  ))
#first plot
ggplot(comp,aes(x=Age,fill=validate))+
  geom_bar()+
  facet_wrap(~validate)

#second plot
ggplot(comp,aes(x=Sex,fill=validate))+
  geom_bar()+
  facet_wrap(~validate)

#third plot
ggplot(race_coded,aes(x=race_encoded,fill=validate))+
  geom_bar()+
  facet_wrap(~validate,scales = "free")+
  theme(
    axis.text.x = element_text(angle=90)
  )

# Accuracy by Threshold the red dot determines the threshold in which maximum accuracy happens. the value of threshold is also printed.

perf <- h2o.performance(death.glm,death.test)
acc_pre_thresh<-h2o.accuracy(perf)
acc_pre_thresh<-acc_pre_thresh%>%mutate(co = (max(accuracy) == accuracy))
ggplot(acc_pre_thresh,aes(threshold,accuracy,label=threshold))+
  geom_line()+
  geom_point(aes(color = co))+
  geom_text(aes(color=co),vjust = 2)+
  scale_color_manual(values = c(NA, "red"))+
  theme(legend.position = "none")

ROC Curve

ROC curve shows the True Positive Rate by False Positive Rate. the optimum point is where TPR is high but FPR has not yet grown.

max_thresh=acc_pre_thresh$threshold[acc_pre_thresh$accuracy==max(acc_pre_thresh$accuracy)]
tpr<-as.data.frame(h2o.tpr(perf))
fpr<-as.data.frame(h2o.fpr(perf))
rates<-inner_join(tpr,fpr)
rates<-rates%>%
  mutate(color=(threshold==max_thresh))

ggplot(rates,aes(fpr,tpr,label =fpr))+
  geom_point(color="gray")+
  geom_point(aes(color = color,size=8))+
  # geom_text(aes(color=color),vjust = 2)+
  scale_color_manual(values = c(NA, "red"))+
  theme(legend.position = "none")+
  labs(
    x="False Positive Rate",
    y="True Positive Rate",
    title="ROC curve"
    )

# building a simple Gradient Boosted Model

death.hex = as.h2o(death, destination_frame= "death.hex")
## 
  |                                                                            
  |                                                                      |   0%
  |                                                                            
  |======================================================================| 100%
death.hex["MannerOfDeath"] <- as.factor(death.hex["MannerOfDeath"] )  
death.split <- h2o.splitFrame(data = death.hex, ratios = 0.8)
death.train <- death.split[[1]]
death.test <- death.split[[2]]
x = setdiff(colnames(death.hex),c("MannerOfDeath","CauseRecode358","CauseRecode113","CauseRecode39"))
y = "MannerOfDeath"

gbm<-h2o.gbm(x,y,death.train,categorical_encoding = "AUTO",stopping_metric = "logloss")

Tuning Parametes

we first start by tuning the depth of model

search_criteria <- list(strategy = "RandomDiscrete", max_models = 36, seed = 1)
hyper_params = list( max_depth = seq(1,29,2) )
my_grid <- h2o.grid("gbm", x = x, y = y,
                      grid_id = "m_grid",
                      training_frame = death.train,
                      validation_frame = death.test,
                      ntrees = 100,
                      seed = 1,
                      hyper_params = hyper_params,
                      search_criteria = search_criteria)
my_grid
## sort the grid models by decreasing AUC
sortedGrid <- h2o.getGrid("m_grid", sort_by="auc", decreasing = TRUE)    
sortedGrid
## find the range of max_depth for the top 5 models
topDepths = sortedGrid@summary_table$max_depth[1:5]                       
minDepth = min(as.numeric(topDepths))
maxDepth = max(as.numeric(topDepths))

now we can tune other parameters

hyper_params = list( 
  max_depth = seq(minDepth,maxDepth,1),                                      
  sample_rate = seq(0.2,1,0.01),                                             
  col_sample_rate = seq(0.2,1,0.01),                                         
  col_sample_rate_per_tree = seq(0.2,1,0.01),                                
  col_sample_rate_change_per_level = seq(0.9,1.1,0.01),                      
  min_rows = 2^seq(0,log2(nrow(death.train))-1,1),                                 
  nbins = 2^seq(4,10,1),                                                     
  nbins_cats = 2^seq(4,12,1),                                                
  min_split_improvement = c(0,1e-8,1e-6,1e-4),                               
  histogram_type = c("UniformAdaptive","QuantilesGlobal","RoundRobin")       
)
search_criteria = list(
  strategy = "RandomDiscrete",      
  max_runtime_secs = 360,         
  max_models = 100,                  
  seed = 1234,                        
  stopping_rounds = 5,                
  stopping_metric = "logloss",
  stopping_tolerance = 1e-3
)
grid <- h2o.grid(
  hyper_params = hyper_params,
  search_criteria = search_criteria,
  algorithm = "gbm",
  grid_id = "best_grid", 
  x = x, 
  y = y, 
  training_frame = death.train, 
  validation_frame = death.test,
  ntrees = 100,                                                            
  learn_rate = 0.05,                                                         
  learn_rate_annealing = 0.99,                                               
  max_runtime_secs = 360,                                                 
  stopping_rounds = 5, stopping_tolerance = 1e-4, stopping_metric = "logloss", 
  score_tree_interval = 10,                                                
  seed = 1                                                             
)
sortedGrid <- h2o.getGrid("best_grid", sort_by = "logloss", decreasing = TRUE)    
sortedGrid
## five best models
for (i in 1:5) {
  gbm <- h2o.getModel(sortedGrid@model_ids[[i]])
  print(h2o.auc(h2o.performance(gbm, valid = TRUE)))
}

best_model=h2o.getModel(sortedGrid@model_ids[[1]])

save(best_model,file="model.RData")
path=h2o.saveModel(best_model,"~/Documents/hesaba/HW6/model" )
